AMS 572 Group Project 16 - Hypothesis Testing on NYC Airbnb Dataset

1.1 Overview In this project, we will be performing Statistical Analysis on the New York Airbnb data by implementing stats modules such as Hypothesis Testing using Tests of Variances (F-test) and two-tailed T test as well as advanced Regression Models. Through this project, we are trying to infer if Prices of Airbnbs in certain cities of NYC lets say in Brooklyn will be greater than prices of Airbnbs in Queens or not. Another hypothesis we look at is whether different parameters like number of reviews, availability of rooms throughout the year, host listings or neighborhood groups has any correlation or impact on the prices of Airbnbs. The results of the tests performed will enable us to find the associativity and dependability of different features on one-another.

1.2 Introduction New York City, as a well-known travel destination, hosted over 66 million visitors in 2019. Airbnb, one of the best-known vacation rental applications, promises to deliver unforgettable travel experiences, containing 30,000 plus listings in New York City 2019. Regardless of the potential economic, social, and environmental impacts, whether they be positive or negative, Airbnb should be considered one of the major competitors in the lodging industry, considering its market share and value (Dogru, 2017b). We were all curious about the reasons why this application attracts so many visitors to choose them. So, we decided to use this data for our data analysis study. Our first interesting guess is whether hotels in different areas in New York City have significant differences in hotel prices. Since Manhattan is a place where every inch of land is precious, it is easy to predict the results of comparing hotel prices in Manhattan with other places, so we finally chose the hotel prices in Brooklyn and Queens for comparison. We also wanted to look at parameters like space, location, neighbourhood groups, availability are reflected on the price of Airbnb accommodation or not since it may play a crucial role on Airbnb guests decision making that will eventually drive the growth of the economy.

1.3 Data Description Our data summaries the information and location of Airbnb hotels in New York comprising of the bookings made in 2019. The listings generate lot of data that can be analyzed and utilized for security purposes, business decisions, detailed understanding of customers and providers behavior on Airbnb platform. The dataset has been obtained from Kaggle which has over 50,000 public datasets available. In our dataset, there are 15 variables, including Airbnb name, Host id, Host Name, Neighborhood groups (comprising of Manhattan, Brooklyn, Queens, Bronx, Staten Island), latitude and longitude (exact location), Room Type(private/shared), Price, Minimum Nights people stayed, Number of Reviews, Last Review Time, Reviews per month, Host Listings on the platform, and Availability of rooms 365 days. Each variable contains 48896 samples in the dataset.

1.4 Hypothesis 1 To check if the price of Airbnb hotels in Queens is different from the price of Airbnb hotels in Brooklyn in 2019. Null hypothesis (H0): Mean price of hotels in Queens(1) equal to mean price of hotels in Brooklyn(2) Alternative hypothesis (Ha): Mean price of hotels in Queens is not equal to mean price of hotels in Brooklyn. H0: 1=2 Ha: 12

Methodology

Since all neighborhood groups are represented as characteristic variables, the first step is to change it to factor variables by using the as.factor function. Then number 2 represents hotels in Brooklyn, number 4 represents hotels in Queens. We can start our statistical analysis. Since our sample size is big, according to the central limit theorem, we can assume that the price of hotels in Queens and the price of hotels in Brooklyn are normally distributed. They are not paired variables, also independent. Now we have two independent, normally distributed variables. We want to use a two sided two sample t-test to do the test. First question is whether two variables share the same variance. After doing var.test, we are sure that they do not share the same variance. With all the information above, we use the t.test function to perform the test with unequal variances. The result shows that the p-value is an extremely small number. Our conclusion is to reject the null hypothesis in favor of alternative hypotheses and conclude that there exists a significant difference between mean price of hotels in Queens and mean price of hotels in Brooklyn.

#Reading NYC Airbnb data set as CSV file
NYC_data <- read.csv("D:/AB_NYC_2019.csv",header = TRUE)
NYC <- as.data.frame(NYC_data)
head(NYC,10)
mydata<-NYC_data
neighbourhood<-as.factor(mydata$neighbourhood_group) 
#1=bronx 2=brooklyn 3=manhattan 4=queens 5=SI
n<-length(mydata$price)
mymatrix<-matrix(c(neighbourhood,mydata$price),ncol = 2,byrow = F)
## Subsetting price of Brooklyn and price of Queens from dataset
price_brooklyn<-mymatrix[which(mymatrix[,1]==2),]
price_queens<-mymatrix[which(mymatrix[,1]==4),]
colnames(price_brooklyn) <- c("1","price_brooklyn") 
col.df <- as.data.frame(price_brooklyn)
col.df<-head(col.df,50)
colnames(price_queens) <- c("1","price_queens")
col.df1 <- as.data.frame(price_queens)
col.df1<-head(col.df1,50)
basket <- cbind(col.df,col.df1)
basket<-basket[,c(2,4)]
head(basket) # Contains prices of Brooklyn and Queens
#variances Test using var.test
var.test(basket$price_brooklyn,basket$price_queens)
## 
##  F test to compare two variances
## 
## data:  basket$price_brooklyn and basket$price_queens
## F = 3.6853, num df = 49, denom df = 49, p-value = 1.105e-05
## alternative hypothesis: true ratio of variances is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  2.091305 6.494146
## sample estimates:
## ratio of variances 
##           3.685273
#2 sided T test with unequal variances
t.test(basket$price_brooklyn, basket$price_queens, var.equal = FALSE)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  basket$price_brooklyn and basket$price_queens
## t = 2.4997, df = 73.769, p-value = 0.01465
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##   9.051248 80.188752
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
##    139.10     94.48
#scatter plot to see correlation between prices of Brooklyn and Queens
# The result shows that the p-value is an extremely small number (<0.05) so we can reject Null hypothesis
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(basket, aes(x=(price_brooklyn), y=(price_queens))) +
    geom_point(shape=1) +    # Use hollow circles
    geom_smooth(method=lm,   # Add linear regression line
                se=FALSE)    # Don't add shaded confidence region
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

1.4.2 Handling Outliers Outliers in dataset Outliers can be harmful because most statistical parameters such as mean, standard deviation and correlation are highly sensitive to outliers. Hence, any statistical calculation based on these parameters is affected by the presence of outliers. Whether it is good or bad to eliminate outliers depends on whether they affect your model positively or negatively. We will be using the IQR (Inter Quartile range) technique to eliminate outliers from specific columns of our dataset. We will be identifying outliers by visualizing them in Boxplots. Boxplots show the median of a dataset along with the first and third quartiles and also the limits beyond which all data values are outliers.

#Using Boxplot to identify outliers and eliminating them using the Inter quartile range function
boxplot(basket)$out

## [1] 299 275 800 250 350 265 192 215
outliers <- function(x) {
  Q1 <- quantile(x, probs=.25)
  Q3 <- quantile(x, probs=.75)
  iqr = Q3-Q1
 upper_limit = Q3 + (iqr*1.5)
 lower_limit = Q1 - (iqr*1.5)
 x > upper_limit | x < lower_limit
}
remove_outliers <- function(df, cols = names(df)) {
  for (col in cols) {
    df <- df[!outliers(df[[col]]),]
  }
  df
}
basket_new<- remove_outliers(basket, c('price_brooklyn', 'price_queens'))
boxplot(basket_new)

#After removing outliers run the variances test to check if 2 variables have same variances or not using F test
var.test(basket_new$price_brooklyn, basket_new$price_queens)
## 
##  F test to compare two variances
## 
## data:  basket_new$price_brooklyn and basket_new$price_queens
## F = 2.8043, num df = 41, denom df = 41, p-value = 0.001313
## alternative hypothesis: true ratio of variances is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  1.507403 5.217161
## sample estimates:
## ratio of variances 
##           2.804347
#Run a 2 sided T test with unequal variances to accept or reject Null hypothesis
t.test (basket_new$price_brooklyn, basket_new$price_queens, var.equal = FALSE)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  basket_new$price_brooklyn and basket_new$price_queens
## t = 4.1495, df = 66.942, p-value = 9.613e-05
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  18.39878 52.50598
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
## 115.97619  80.52381
#scatter plot to see negative correlation between prices of Brooklyn and Queens
# The result shows that the p-value is an extremely small number (<0.05) so we can reject Null hypothesis same as original analysis
ggplot(basket_new, aes(x=(price_brooklyn), y=(price_queens))) +
    geom_point(shape=1) +    # Use hollow circles
    geom_smooth(method=lm,   # Add linear regression line
                se=FALSE)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Conclusion

After eliminating outliers, the p-value is still less than 0.05 similar to original observation which confirms that we can reject the Null hypothesis and conclude the mean prices of Airbnb in Brooklyn is not same as Mean prices of Airbnb in Queens. Also, the graph now eliminates possible outliers and depicts a negative association between prices of Brooklyn and Queens.

1.4.3 Missing Values Analysis

The next part of Hypothesis 1 is to investigate effect of Missing Values on our hypothesis 1. In statistics, missing values occur when there is no data input for the variable in the observation. Missing data are common occurrence but may have significant impact on conclusions. We will proceed with the dataset that we fixed after removing outliers from previous section. We will be simulating 2 types of Missing Values MCAR and MNAR on our dataset and discuss how we will be handling the missing values and then re analyse and examine the impact for Hypothesis 1. Missing Completely at Random (MCAR)

MCAR stands for Missing Completely at Random where the missing values are unrelated to any feature, just as the name denotes. In MCAR, the propensity for a data point to be missing is completely random. There does not exist any relationship between a data point missing and any values in the data set, observed or missing.

Methodology

Method 1: Using simFrame package to simulate missing values Completely at Random

Since we do not have any missing value in the price variables, we will use a R package called simFrame to insert some random missing values. The advantage of using this package is that we can control the missing rate. We decided to let the missing at random rate to be 20% and 50%. By using the delete missing values method, we delete all the missing values under the price variable (use na.omit function). Then we will test hypothesis 1 using var.test (check if variables have equal variances) and a two-sided t test (without equal variance assumption) to reject or accept Null hypothesis.

#install.packages("simFrame")
library(simFrame)
## Warning: package 'simFrame' was built under R version 3.6.3
## Loading required package: Rcpp
## Warning: package 'Rcpp' was built under R version 3.6.3
## Loading required package: lattice
## Warning: package 'lattice' was built under R version 3.6.3
## Loading required package: parallel
nac<-NAControl(NArate=0.2)
x<-setNA(NYC,nac)
neighbourhood_MAR=as.factor(x$neighbourhood_group) 
mymatrix_MAR=matrix(c(neighbourhood_MAR,x$price),ncol = 2,byrow = F)

## method: delete missing values
newdata=na.omit(mymatrix_MAR)
price_brooklyn_MAR=newdata[which(newdata[,1]==2),]
price_queens_MAR=newdata[which(newdata[,1]==4),]

###check equal variance assumption
var.test(price_brooklyn_MAR[,2],price_queens_MAR[,2])
## 
##  F test to compare two variances
## 
## data:  price_brooklyn_MAR[, 2] and price_queens_MAR[, 2]
## F = 5.3479, num df = 10563, denom df = 2923, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true ratio of variances is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  5.044394 5.664131
## sample estimates:
## ratio of variances 
##           5.347865
##conclusion: the p-value is extremely small. Implies unequal variance.

###two sample t-test with unequal variance
t.test(price_brooklyn_MAR[,2],price_queens_MAR[,2],var.equal = FALSE)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  price_brooklyn_MAR[, 2] and price_queens_MAR[, 2]
## t = 12.718, df = 11194, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  25.64261 34.98754
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
## 122.81986  92.50479

Method 2: Using MICE Package to simulate Missing Values Completely at Random

We will be using another method to handle the missing values. Due to incompleteness of missing elements in the Airbnb dataset we use Ampute() function of Mice package in R to insert missing values completely at Random on the entire dataset with a proportion of missingness of 20% and 50%. We will also use Mice which uses multivariate imputations to estimate the missing values. Multiple imputations help in resolving the uncertainty for the missingness. The package regresses over any variable that contains missing values and predicts missing values. One of the available models are PMM (Predictive Mean Matching) which is suitable for numeric variables. For each missing entry, the PMM method creates a reduced set of candidate donors (typically with 3, 5 or 10 members) from all complete cases that have predicted values near to the predicted value for the missing value. One donor is randomly picked from the candidates, and the observed value of the donor replaces the missing value. The assumption is that the distribution of the missing cell is equal to the observed data of the candidate donors.

Using MICE ampute() function at 20% and 50% missing rates

library(mice) ###using Mice function

Conclusion

Using Mice at missing rate proportion of 20%, we see that approximately 74% of the entire dataset had no missing values and 14% missing values were introduced for prices of Brooklyn and 12% missing values for Queens prices (Chart 1). Similarly, when we set 50% missing rate, we see that 26% of missing values were introduced for Prices of Queens and 24% for Brooklyn (Chart 2). The Mice function uses PMM (Predictive Mean matching) method to estimate missing values at random. We then use var.test to double check after deleting all the missing values, if the two variables have the same variance. Then perform a two-sided t test without equal variance assumption. Both Method 1 (using simFrame) and Method 2 (using Mice) show a p-value < 0.05 which rejects the null hypothesis in favor of the alternative hypothesis and conclude that there is a significant difference between the price of hotels in Queens and the price of hotels in Brooklyn at both 20% and 50% missing rates. Now we are confident to say that when the missing at random rate is under 50%, deleting all the missing variables does not affect the final conclusion in our study.

Missing Not at Random (MNAR)

MNAR means that the probability of data missing varies for reasons that are unknown to us. For example, the weighing scale mechanism may wear out as time passes and can produce more missing data as time progresses but that is something we may fail to notice.

In this project, we will be using 2 methods to analyse MNAR values - Replacing the first 1000 elements in the price of hotels in Brooklyn with missing variables and second method is the Mice package to simulate MNAR values and estimating MNAR values using PMM (predictive mean matching technique).After simulating the missing data, we will check equal variances assumption and 2-sided T- test to check if price of Airbnb hotels in Queens is different from the price of Airbnb hotels in Brooklyn

Methodology

Method 1: We replace the first 1000 elements in the price of hotels in Brooklyn with missing variables. This case the missing values are non-ignorable missing values. We use na.omit function to delete all missing not at random values

price_brooklyn_MNAR=replace(price_brooklyn[,2],1:1000,NA)
# We decided to replace first 1000 values in price in Brooklyn to be missing values
# Instead of missing at random, this time we made variables missing not at random
# and keep price in Queens complete.
new_price_brooklyn_MNAR=na.omit(price_brooklyn_MNAR)
###check equal variance assumption
var.test(new_price_brooklyn_MNAR,price_queens[,2])
## 
##  F test to compare two variances
## 
## data:  new_price_brooklyn_MNAR and price_queens[, 2]
## F = 1.057, num df = 15440, denom df = 4571, p-value = 0.02085
## alternative hypothesis: true ratio of variances is not equal to 1
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  1.008465 1.107146
## sample estimates:
## ratio of variances 
##           1.056971
##conclusion: the p-value is extremely small. Implies unequal variance.

###two sample t-test with unequal variance
t.test(new_price_brooklyn_MNAR,price_queens_MAR[,2],var.equal = FALSE)
## 
##  Welch Two Sample t-test
## 
## data:  new_price_brooklyn_MNAR and price_queens_MAR[, 2]
## t = 13.358, df = 8781.3, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true difference in means is not equal to 0
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  23.44684 31.51198
## sample estimates:
## mean of x mean of y 
## 119.98420  92.50479

Method 2: Using MICE Package to simulate Missing Values Not at Random

Similarly as MCAR, we feed in desired columns of the Airbnb dataset into the Ampute() function setting method as MNAR in the Mice library package to simulate missing values Not at Random with a proportion of missingness equal to 20% and 50%. We then use Mice to estimate the missing values using multiple imputation technique like PMM. Multiple imputations help in resolving the uncertainty for the missingness. The package regresses over any variable that contains missing values and predicts missing values. After simulating missing values not at random in our dataset we imply the Equal Variances assumption to check if 2 variables have the same variances or not and a two tailed T test to accept or reject hypothesis 1.

library(mice) ###using Mice function
miss_data.hyp1<-ampute(basket_new,mech="MNAR",prop=0.2) ### using 20% proportion
md.MNAR.hyp4<-miss_data.hyp1$amp
which(is.na(md.MNAR.hyp4)=="TRUE")

                se=FALSE)    # Don't add shaded confidence region
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Conclusion

From method 1 and Method 2 for MNAR analysis, we see that for the equal variance assumption, the variables do not have the same variances. And, using a two-sided sample t-test, we get the same conclusion. The p-value is extremely small, and we can reject the null hypothesis in favour of the alternative hypothesis. As we increase the missing rate to 50%, we see that around 36% of missing values has been simulated for Brooklyn and 19% for Queens prices using ampute() function of Mice (Chart 2). Mice function was also used to estimate missing values Not at Random with the help of PMM (Predictive Mean matching method). The conclusion still holds the same. The p-value is <0.05 and we can reject the null hypothesis in favor of the alternative hypothesis and conclude that there is a significant difference between the prices of Brooklyn verses prices of Queens both at missing rates of 20% and 50%.

1.4 Hypothesis 2 Advanced Model: Multi Linear Regression

Hypothesis 2: Does the neighbourhood, latitude, longitude, room type, minimum nights, number of reviews, reviews per month, calculated host listing count and availability (365 days) affect the price of Airbnb in NYC? We will also compare the reduced model with full model (with all parameters) and check if it is a better fit or not. H0: 1 = 2 = 3 = 4 = 5 = 5 = 6 = 7 = 8 = 9 = 0 H1: At least one of 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, 9 0

Data Assumptions of Multi Linear Regression

The regression coefficient 1 is interpreted as the expected change in Y associated with a 1-unit increase in x1 while x2,, xp are held fixed. A linear regression model that contains greater than one predictor variable is called a multiple linear regression model. For example: the below model is a multiple linear regression model with two predictor variables, x1 and x2. The model is linear because it is linear in the parameters 0, 1 and 2

Y=0+1x1+2x2+

Dependent Variable: In our hypothesis, the dependent variable is price (Y). Independent Variable: The independent variables x1, x2, x3, x4, x5, x6, x7, x8, x9 in the dataset are neighborhood groups, latitude, longitude, room type, minimum nights people stayed, number of reviews, reviews per month, calculated host listing count and availability_365.

Below we produce a table of Pearsons correlation coefficients. From this output table, we can see that longitude has the strongest relationship with price (r = -0.16), and reviews per month has the weakest correlation with price (Y).

Conclusion

The summary() table contains the coefficients for the regression equation, tests of significance for each variable and R squared value. The last column contains the p-values for each of the independent variables. The hypothesis being tested for each is that the coefficient is 0 after controlling for the other variables. For example, lets say the effects of other variables are removed before assessing the relationship between the latitude and price. A p-value < 0.05, provides evidence that the coefficient is different to 0. We can see that the results of the full model linear regression (with all parameters) show the significance of each individual variable, where majority of the parameters are significant at the 5% level. But, the multiple R-squared value is 0.1181 or 11.8% which is much less than 0.5, so the linear relationship is not obvious.

Also, from the Normal Q-Q plot, we can see that it does not satisfy linear model assumptions (Normal Q-Q plot should be straight line). So, we built the second model by removing possible outliers.

## second model after removing outliers
NYC1 <- NYC %>% mutate(id = row_number())
AB_NYC_2019_model2 <- NYC1 %>% sample_frac(.7) %>% filter(price > 0)

my_data <- AB_NYC_2019_model2 %>% filter(price < quantile(AB_NYC_2019_model2$price, 0.9) & price > quantile(AB_NYC_2019_model2$price, 0.1)) %>% tidyr::drop_na()
#Running regression 2
model2 <- lm(log(price) ~ latitude + longitude + room_type + minimum_nights  + number_of_reviews + reviews_per_month + calculated_host_listings_count+ availability_365 + neighbourhood_group, data = my_data)
summary(model2) #summarize coefficients table

##     data = my_data)

## (Intercept)                      -1.300e+02  6.467e+00  -20.101  < 2e-16 ***
## latitude                         -4.648e-01  6.326e-02   -7.348 2.09e-13 ***
## longitude                        -2.079e+00  7.285e-02  -28.541  < 2e-16 ***
## room_typePrivate room            -5.181e-01  4.309e-03 -120.225  < 2e-16 ***
## room_typeShared room             -6.361e-01  1.997e-02  -31.858  < 2e-16 ***
## minimum_nights                   -1.393e-03  1.276e-04  -10.920  < 2e-16 ***
## number_of_reviews                -1.754e-05  5.228e-05   -0.336   0.7372    
## reviews_per_month                -1.769e-03  1.570e-03   -1.126   0.2600    
## calculated_host_listings_count    5.018e-04  9.149e-05    5.484 4.19e-08 ***
## availability_365                  3.053e-04  1.784e-05   17.112  < 2e-16 ***
## neighbourhood_groupBrooklyn      -3.912e-02  1.869e-02   -2.093   0.0364 *  
## neighbourhood_groupManhattan      1.462e-01  1.711e-02    8.543  < 2e-16 ***

## Multiple R-squared:  0.4939, Adjusted R-squared:  0.4936 
## F-statistic:  1608 on 13 and 21418 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16
#ANOVA
anova(model2)
#Residual Analysis
par(mfrow=c(1,3))
plot(model2, which=1, col=c("blue")) # Residuals vs Fitted Plot
plot(model2, which=2, col=c("red"))  # Q-Q Plot
plot(model2, which=3, col=c("blue"))  # Scale-Location Plot

plot(model2, which=5, col=c("blue"))  # Residuals vs Leverage

Conclusion

From the output of the second model, we see that multiple R-squared is 0.496 (~50%) which is close to 0.5, so the linear relationship is more obvious than the first model. The p-value (2.2e-16) < 0.05, provides evidence that the coefficient is not 0 that means exists at least one of _1, _2, _3, _4, _5, _6, _7, _8, _9 0. The Latitude, longitude, room type, minimum_nights, reviews_per_month, calculated_host_listings_count, availability_365 and neighbourhood_groups are all significant predictors of price (from Anova analysis). Also, from the Normal Q-Q plot, we can see that the model satisfies linear model assumptions along with rest of the model assumptions like constant variance from Residual plot. Since the independent value is significant, we can explain the relationship between the independent and dependent variables using the Estimate column. The Estimate column in the coefficients table, gives us the coefficients for each independent variable in the regression model.

The R^2 value increases with the number of independent variables so it is better to use the adjusted R^2 value especially when comparing models. The adjusted R^2 indicates that 49.7% of the variation in price can be explained by the model containing latitude, longitude, room_type, minimum_nights, reviews_per_month, calculated_host_listings_count, availability_365 and neighbourhood_group which is quite high so predictions from the regression equation are fairly reliable. We can conclude from the above test that we reject Null hypothesis (H0) in favor of alternative hypothesis and except the parameter number of reviews other variables do impact prices ie. atleast one of _1, _2, _3, _4, _5, _6, _7, _8, _9 0 Reduced Model A reduced model does not take into account all the possible variables. We reduce a model if terms are not significant or if we need additional error degrees of freedom. We assume that certain terms (not all) are zero. We will try to run analysis on just 4 parameters using reduced model and compare with full model. price ~ minimum_nights + number_of_reviews + reviews_per_month + availability_365

#Regression on the reduced model
data.mout<-my_data[c(10,11,12,14,16)] # subsetting data
#Running regression
model3 <- lm(price~  minimum_nights +number_of_reviews+reviews_per_month +availability_365  , data =data.mout)
summary(model3)

Hence, we can conclude that model 2 (full model after removing outliers) is a much better fit as compared to reduced model which provides a holistic information about the correlation of different parameters with price. 1.4.2 Missing Values Analysis Missing Completely at Random As discussed in Hypothesis 1, in MCAR, the propensity for a data point to be missing is completely random. We will be using the Mice function to simulate missing values in the dataset at a missing rate of 20% and 50% (after removing outliers from dataset) and then use multiple imputation function of Mice to estimate the missing value. We will then feed the dataset into the multi regression model and check if we can accept or reject the null hypothesis 2.

Using Ampute() function of Mice package at 20% missing rate

#Missing Completely at Random

library(corrplot)

miss_data.hyp2.1<-ampute(my_data_new,mech="MCAR",prop=0.2) ### using 20% proportion
md.MCAR.hyp3.1<-miss_data.hyp2.1$amp
which(is.na(md.MCAR.hyp3.1)=="TRUE")

plot(model.MCAR, which=5, col=c("blue")) #residual vs Leverage

Conclusion

From the output of the MCAR model, we see that multiple R-squared is around (0.46) 46% for both 20% and 50% missing rates which is close to 0.5, so the linear relationship is more obvious. The p-value (2.2e-16) < 0.05, provides evidence that the coefficient is not 0 that means there exist at least one of _1, _2, _3, _4, _5, _6, _7, _8, _9 0 for the MCAR model at 20% as well as 50 %. From the Anova table, we see that all parameters except number of reviews have impact on prices at 20% missing rate while all parameters except number of reviews as well as reviews per month affects prices when we increase the missing rate completely at random to 50%. Also, from the Normal Q-Q plot, we can see that the model satisfies linear relationship. Also, the residuals are approximately normally distributed. In the residual vs predicted plot, we see that residuals are randomly scattered around the centre line with no obvious non-random patterns which suggests constant variance. Hence, the MCAR model shows similar observations that of original full model. We can reject the Null hypothesis and conclude there exists multiple parameters that affect prices of Airbnb in NYC for MCAR model.

Missing Values Not at Random

We will again use Mice package to simulate MNAR values and estimate missing values using Mice Multiple Imputation technique such as PMM (predictive mean matching technique). After simulating the missing data, we feed the dataset into multilinear regression model and check if hypothesis 2 is satisfied or not.

#Missing Values not at Random
miss_data.hyp2.5<-ampute(my_data_new,mech="MNAR",prop=0.2) ### using 20% proportion
## Warning: Data is made numeric because the calculation of weights requires

Conclusion

From the output of the MNAR model, we see that multiple R-squared is around (0.42) 42% for a missing rate of 20% which is close to 0.5, so the linear relationship is more obvious. The p-value (2.2e-16) < 0.05, provides evidence that the coefficients are not 0 that means there exist at least one of _1, _2, _3, _4, _5, _6, _7, _8, _9 0 for the MNAR model at 20%. From the Anova table, we see that 6 out of 9 parameters are significant and we can reject the Null hypothesis again and conclude that multiple parameters do impact prices of Airbnb for MNAR model as well. From the residual plots we see that all model assumptions are fulfilled. When we increase the missing rate not at random to 50% the conclusion still holds true.

1.5 Summary and Conclusions

According to all the discussion we did, our final conclusion for the first hypothesis is that there is a significant difference between hotel price in Queens and hotel price in Brooklyn. When we have missing values and the missing rate is less than 50%, we can delete all the missing values and get the same conclusion. Moreover, we can use a specific R package to complete the missing values. Comparing the two methods to deal with the missing values (missing at random and missing not at random cases), there is no significant difference in analysis between the two methods. However, if we have data with a missing rate greater than 50%, it is better to use the Mice package in R to insert missing values.

Using multiple linear regression to investigate the relationship between price and multiple variables, our final conclusion for hypothesis 2 is that we reject the null hypothesis and deduce that multiple variables like neighbourhood groups, availability of Airbnb, host listings, room types does affect the price of Airbnb in NYC. The adjusted R^2 value significantly increased when we removed outliers from dataset and a full model with all parameters is a better fit as compared to a reduced model. Consequently, the data met the assumptions of homogeneity of variance and linearity and the residuals were approximately normally distributed. The conclusion also holds true for Missing Value analysis (MCAR and MNAR) where we reject the Null hypothesis and favour alternate hypothesis such that there exists at least one of _1, _2, _3, _4, _5, _6, _7, _8, _9 0.
